Dialogue: 0,0:01:40.92,0:01:43.93,Default,,0,0,0,,April 1943.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:43.93,0:01:51.08,Default,,0,0,0,,The Japanese garrisons were mounting a fierce resistance to the US Army that had already recaptured Guadalcanal
Dialogue: 0,0:01:51.08,0:01:54.69,Default,,0,0,0,,and was now steadily advancing along the Solomon Islands. {nc what's shimazutai}
Dialogue: 0,0:01:55.86,0:01:59.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Commander-in-Chief of the Combined Fleet \NAdmiral Yamamoto lsoroku
Dialogue: 0,0:01:59.82,0:02:05.81,Default,,0,0,0,,flew over from the Truk Island to the front line base \Non Rabaul for an in-person inspection.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:06.37,0:02:07.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Attention!
Dialogue: 0,0:02:09.11,0:02:10.15,Default,,0,0,0,,Salute! {ha's, no clue}
Dialogue: 0,0:02:27.21,0:02:29.96,Default,,0,0,0,,There, what did I tell you? \NA Japanese transmission! {nc what's first part, could be "there, it came!"}
Dialogue: 0,0:02:33.17,0:02:39.18,Default,,0,0,0,,The Military Intelligence Service, incorporated \Ninto the United States Pacific Fleet Headquarters in Hawaii,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:39.18,0:02:44.27,Default,,0,0,0,,was holed up in a top secret basement, \Nonly accessible to the cryptanalysis staff.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:49.83,0:02:56.37,Default,,0,0,0,,All the Japanese Navy transmissions, intercepted \Nin various areas of the Southern Pacific, gather here.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:56.91,0:03:07.06,Default,,0,0,0,,This electric decoding machine was designed and developed by the US' leading cryptanalyst, Major Thomas Dyer. {https://www.usni.org/magazines/proceedings/2012/june/lead-code-breaker-midway}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:07.06,0:03:13.55,Default,,0,0,0,,It has been enhanced to the point where it could effortlessly decipher the Japanese Navy's encrypted transmissions.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:14.44,0:03:19.57,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fs40}monisaa monyo nsachiichii haka moniraha no sude no suhato bunsai da suma rufu gari {モニサア モンヨ ンサチイチイ ハカ モニラハ ノ スデ ノ スハト ブンサイ ダ スマ ルフ ガリ}
Dialogue: 0,0:03:19.57,0:03:21.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Hey, take a look at this.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:22.43,0:03:26.48,Default,,0,0,0,,What's the meaning of this? \NIt doesn't look like a Japanese sentence.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:28.45,0:03:30.44,Default,,0,0,0,,I wonder if the machine broke.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:32.08,0:03:33.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Look at this, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:34.69,0:03:38.20,Default,,0,0,0,,I can't understand it. \NCall Major Dyer here at once. It's urgent!
Dialogue: 0,0:03:41.22,0:03:48.21,Sign,,0,0,270,,{\fade(600,0)\b1\blur1\bord0\c&HE3E5E7&}Episode 18 \N{\fs120}Operation Vengeance
Dialogue: 0,0:04:02.72,0:04:03.93,Default,,0,0,0,,Major Dyer.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:07.28,0:04:09.20,Default,,0,0,0,,The machine didn't break.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:09.20,0:04:11.77,Default,,0,0,0,,The Japanese Navy changed their cypher. {it's important to differentiate cypher from code: code is what a real word is substituted with in the message, cypher is how the message is encrypted, cypher is to be decrypted by machine, code by humans}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:12.40,0:04:14.37,Default,,0,0,0,,Did they replace it entirely?
Dialogue: 0,0:04:14.37,0:04:15.26,Default,,0,0,0,,I don't know.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:15.92,0:04:19.78,Default,,0,0,0,,But if they really did, \Nthis machine is no longer of any use to us.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:19.78,0:04:24.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Then we need to manufacture a new decoder, don't we? \NHow long do you think it will take?
Dialogue: 0,0:04:24.76,0:04:26.60,Default,,0,0,0,,It usually takes about half a year.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:26.60,0:04:31.05,Default,,0,0,0,,However, the cypher isn't necessarily \Nchanged entirely every time.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:31.05,0:04:33.37,Default,,0,0,0,,At any rate, start by cracking this cypher.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:33.37,0:04:34.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Roger!
Dialogue: 0,0:04:35.20,0:04:40.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Listen, we need to decipher this, whatever it takes. \NWork around the clock! 24/7 until we crack it! {/stay up all night, stay up every night ...}
Dialogue: 0,0:04:40.18,0:04:41.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Roger!
Dialogue: 0,0:05:03.47,0:05:10.06,Default,,0,0,0,,If a war breaks out with the US and the UK, how far can our fleet take us before it's stopped in its tracks? {lit: how far can they make it}
Dialogue: 0,0:05:10.06,0:05:11.89,Default,,0,0,0,,I'm a soldier.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:11.89,0:05:13.95,Default,,0,0,0,,I'll keep going for as long as you order me. {lit: if I'm told to do it, I'll do it}
Dialogue: 0,0:05:13.95,0:05:17.85,Default,,0,0,0,,For the first half a year or a maybe a year, \Nwe'll have a free rein, I believe. {lit: will rage/be wild to one's heart's content/to the full}
Dialogue: 0,0:05:17.85,0:05:21.53,Default,,0,0,0,,However, I cannot promise anything \Nbeyond that time frame.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:25.99,0:05:27.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Just a dream?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:28.41,0:05:32.56,Default,,0,0,0,,The one year time frame I gave to our fleet \Nhas run out long ago.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:45.13,0:05:46.09,Default,,0,0,0,,Who's there?!
Dialogue: 0,0:05:47.47,0:05:48.76,Default,,0,0,0,,My apologies, sir!
Dialogue: 0,0:05:49.72,0:05:54.91,Default,,0,0,0,,I had a bad dream and so I woke up. \NYou don't mind me walking to the beach?
Dialogue: 0,0:05:54.91,0:05:56.59,Default,,0,0,0,,For sure! I'll accompany you.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:14.95,0:06:16.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Admiral, use this.{no clue what's this cloth he's offering or what he's offering it for}
Dialogue: 0,0:06:16.43,0:06:17.59,Default,,0,0,0,,No,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:18.25,0:06:20.17,Default,,0,0,0,,I like it better this way.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:21.42,0:06:25.16,Default,,0,0,0,,You'd never think that a war rages on this ocean.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:26.13,0:06:28.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Have you been stationed somewhere else before Rabaul?
Dialogue: 0,0:06:28.99,0:06:32.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes. I was transferred from Bougainville \Nthree months ago.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:32.28,0:06:34.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Oh? So you've been to the front line?
Dialogue: 0,0:06:34.99,0:06:36.66,Default,,0,0,0,,How is it looking over there?
Dialogue: 0,0:06:36.66,0:06:41.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Sir. The Bougainville garrison \Nis woefully undermanned. {no clue why he says "reserve corps", assumed "garrison is poor; meagre; meager; feeble; scanty; shabby; insubstantial​" tho japanese have other word for that}
Dialogue: 0,0:06:41.33,0:06:43.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Are you finding Rabaul that much better? {nc: そんなにラバウルはいいか}
Dialogue: 0,0:06:44.02,0:06:45.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:45.00,0:06:50.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Thanks to coming to Rabaul, I got to meet \Nthe Commander-in-Chief of the Combined Fleet in person.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:52.57,0:06:53.68,Default,,0,0,0,,At ease. {/relax}
Dialogue: 0,0:06:53.68,0:06:54.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:54.78,0:06:58.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Are you really that happy to see me here in Rabaul?
Dialogue: 0,0:06:59.30,0:07:03.28,Default,,0,0,0,,Yes. You are the guardian deity of our Imperial Fleet.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:03.71,0:07:04.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Like a god.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:05.55,0:07:11.87,Default,,0,0,0,,You're exaggerating. I drink alcohol too. And I'm \Nfond of gambling. Where have you seen a god like that?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:11.87,0:07:17.87,Default,,0,0,0,,That's exactly why you {\i1}are{\i0} a God. \NYou're one of us. Like a god in human form! {act. says "right next to us" but I can't come up with a good english wording for it, though I sense there is some good word for it somewhere in the recesses of my mind}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:17.87,0:07:23.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Those fellows in Bougainville don't get to meet the God in person. That's the saddest part of it. {lit: can't worship the god directly}
Dialogue: 0,0:07:28.28,0:07:30.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Bougainville, huh?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:30.03,0:07:31.47,Default,,0,0,0,,Bougainville.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:41.67,0:07:44.81,Default,,0,0,0,,Hey, how does it feel to be carrying God?
Dialogue: 0,0:07:44.81,0:07:47.99,Default,,0,0,0,,Sir. I feel like I'm atoning for my sins. I'm so happy. {actually "to incur the wrath of the gods (e.g. by doing something immoral); to incur divine punishment; to pay for one's sins"}
Dialogue: 0,0:08:05.27,0:08:06.26,Default,,0,0,0,,I got it!
Dialogue: 0,0:08:06.77,0:08:07.63,Default,,0,0,0,,I solved it!
Dialogue: 0,0:08:11.88,0:08:14.74,Default,,0,0,0,,We no longer need to work the midnight oil! {/work around the clock}
Dialogue: 0,0:08:14.74,0:08:16.02,Default,,0,0,0,,We broke the cypher!
Dialogue: 0,0:08:20.50,0:08:23.06,Default,,0,0,0,,The Japanese Navy didn't change the cypher,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:23.06,0:08:25.41,Default,,0,0,0,,only slightly altered the random numbers table.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:25.41,0:08:28.14,Default,,0,0,0,,Just input that change into the machine \Nand it'll be good to go!
Dialogue: 0,0:08:28.14,0:08:30.62,Default,,0,0,0,,Then, we can still use that decoding machine?
Dialogue: 0,0:08:30.62,0:08:31.25,Default,,0,0,0,,Certainly!
Comment: 0,0:08:32.13,0:08:35.76,Sign,,0,0,0,,{ignoring this sign because I'm too lazy to crop in sync with him moving finger}
Dialogue: 0,0:08:32.59,0:08:36.26,Default,,0,0,0,,You're already in Rabaul. \NMight as well stop by at Bougainville.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:36.26,0:08:39.54,Default,,0,0,0,,Bougainville is another 500 km from here. It's dangerous.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:39.54,0:08:43.44,Default,,0,0,0,,For the moment, we still retain \Nair superiority over this area.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:43.44,0:08:45.51,Default,,0,0,0,,I'll be flying with an escort, so it's fine.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:45.51,0:08:49.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Still, our air superiority is contested heavily.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:49.60,0:08:51.90,Default,,0,0,0,,An enemy plane may appear when you least expect.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:52.49,0:08:53.95,Default,,0,0,0,,Pardon me chiming in,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:54.57,0:08:58.85,Default,,0,0,0,,but I also believe that the Supreme Commander \Nhas no business leaving the safe area.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:58.85,0:09:03.30,Default,,0,0,0,,The Imperial Fleet may come under attack \Nat that exact moment when you're away. {nc what he means: 長官がそれをなさるときは帝国海軍が滅びる時ですよ - the time when commander does that is the time when the IJN is destroyed/will perish}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:03.30,0:09:05.87,Default,,0,0,0,,Logically, your arguments are irrefutable.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:06.33,0:09:09.44,Default,,0,0,0,,But thing is, I want to go there.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:09.44,0:09:13.01,Default,,0,0,0,,What's the good of me coming \Nall the way to Rabaul just to turn back at once? {nc what he means again: 山本がわざわざラバールまで来て何の役に立つのか - added "just to turn back"}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:13.47,0:09:17.22,Default,,0,0,0,,For our soldiers, defending various small islands all across the Pacific...
Dialogue: 0,0:09:17.22,0:09:24.10,Default,,0,0,0,,"Hey, Yamamoto is here. Get yourself together..." There's nothing much I can do for them, except come there myself. {again no clue: おい山本が来たぜしっかりやれよと 顔を見せるぐらいしかすることがないじゃないか}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:24.10,0:09:29.27,Default,,0,0,0,,"If even Yamamoto himself showed up, \NI guess this front line of ours ain't so scary, after all."
Dialogue: 0,0:09:29.27,0:09:30.89,Default,,0,0,0,,That's what I want to instill in them.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:30.89,0:09:33.23,Default,,0,0,0,,Admiral, I submit to your decision. {lit: I understand well}
Dialogue: 0,0:09:35.24,0:09:37.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Nice. Come out, come out!
Dialogue: 0,0:09:39.91,0:09:41.87,Default,,0,0,0,,W-We've an emergency!
Dialogue: 0,0:09:51.49,0:09:53.49,Default,,0,0,0,,This is big news!
Dialogue: 0,0:09:54.96,0:09:57.54,Default,,0,0,0,,Put me through to Commander Layton. It's urgent! {https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edwin_T._Layton#World_War_II}
Dialogue: 0,0:10:00.05,0:10:01.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Commander Layton here!
Dialogue: 0,0:10:25.08,0:10:29.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Could Yamamoto really be so careless \Nas to slip up so foolishly?
Dialogue: 0,0:10:29.46,0:10:32.42,Default,,0,0,0,,It's too good to be true. \NIt has to be a trap of sorts.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:35.53,0:10:37.53,Default,,0,0,0,,Listen here, you bastards! {guess, only hear kisama .... kike}
Dialogue: 0,0:10:38.20,0:10:41.15,Default,,0,0,0,,You blockheads! \NWho was smart enough to type this telegram?! {guess, I'm not finding any mention of this telegram being a mistake, apparently there was nothing special in how it was sent, just that they didn't know their codes were cracked}
Dialogue: 0,0:10:42.54,0:10:46.13,Default,,0,0,0,,Did someone really think it's a good idea \Nto radio the admiral's itinerary in detail?! {act. comb. fleet. comm.}
Dialogue: 0,0:10:46.81,0:10:49.62,Default,,0,0,0,,It's like sending the enemy an invitation to join him!
Dialogue: 0,0:10:49.62,0:10:53.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Inform Admiral Yamamoto \Nthat I flew out of Bougainville to meet him! {added, no clue what's the point of just telling him "I flew out"}
Dialogue: 0,0:10:57.74,0:11:02.33,Default,,0,0,0,,Admiral. As long as I oversee the defense of Bougainville, \Nit's absolutely impregnable!
Dialogue: 0,0:11:02.33,0:11:04.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Please cancel your visit.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:04.66,0:11:08.25,Default,,0,0,0,,I'm not going there \Nbecause I don't trust you with the defense of it.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:08.25,0:11:13.52,Default,,0,0,0,,I understand, sir. Still, why did you have to radio out \Na precise itinerary of your inspection tour?
Dialogue: 0,0:11:13.52,0:11:16.71,Default,,0,0,0,,What if US Intelligence intercepts this transmission?
Dialogue: 0,0:11:16.71,0:11:20.98,Default,,0,0,0,,They may have broken our cyphers. \NOr they may have not.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:20.98,0:11:23.85,Default,,0,0,0,,Usually, it takes them a while to do it. {lit: normally, they can't break it at first}
Dialogue: 0,0:11:23.85,0:11:28.39,Default,,0,0,0,,I can't afford worrying about every little thing, \Nlosing this great joy in the process. {毎日のことを考えて大きな喜びを失うことはできない - no clue, "I can't lose great happiness thinking about everyday things"; was "I cannot lose great joy in the unlikely event." in HA}
Dialogue: 0,0:11:39.94,0:11:45.04,Default,,0,0,0,,Secretary Knox, do you believe \Nthe contents of this Japanese telegram? {no clue what's his rank really, guess}{legend: President Franklin D. Roosevelt may have authorized Secretary of the Navy Frank Knox to "get Yamamoto", but no official record of such an order exists,[4] and sources disagree whether he did so.[5] Knox essentially let Admiral Chester W. Nimitz make the decision.[5] Nimitz first consulted Admiral William F. Halsey Jr., Commander, South Pacific, and then authorized the mission on 17 April.}{https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frank_Knox#World_War_II}
Dialogue: 0,0:11:45.04,0:11:51.21,Default,,0,0,0,,The honor of making this judgment belongs \Nto the US Pacific Fleet Commander-in-Chief Admiral Nimitz.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:51.21,0:11:52.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Come in.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:55.00,0:11:58.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Top secret telegram from Dutch Harbor in Alaska. {legend: Although this message was first met with skepticism that the Japanese would be so careless, other MIS linguists in Alaska and Hawaii had also intercepted the same message, confirming its accuracy.[3]}
Dialogue: 0,0:12:01.91,0:12:03.21,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's see.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:03.21,0:12:08.51,Default,,0,0,0,,"As arranged previously, on April 18th, the Commander-in-Chief of the Combined Fleet Yamamoto
Dialogue: 0,0:12:08.51,0:12:13.00,Default,,0,0,0,,will visit Ballalae, Shortland, and Buin \Nwith a front line inspection.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:13.00,0:12:17.00,Default,,0,0,0,,6 a.m." - This must be in standard Japanese time. {nc why he says "rabaul's japanese time"}
Dialogue: 0,0:12:17.00,0:12:22.07,Default,,0,0,0,,"Riding the Navy Type 1 attack bomber \Nand with an escort of 6 Zero fighters, take off from Rabaul. {https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mitsubishi_G4M}
Dialogue: 0,0:12:22.07,0:12:24.76,Default,,0,0,0,,8 a.m. - Arrive at Bougainville."
Dialogue: 0,0:12:26.06,0:12:29.23,Default,,0,0,0,,It mirrors exactly the contents \Nof the telegram received by Hawaii.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:29.23,0:12:32.08,Default,,0,0,0,,So they caught this encrypted transmission in Alaska as well...
Dialogue: 0,0:12:32.56,0:12:36.58,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, what is their game, \Nsending it over such a strong frequency?
Dialogue: 0,0:12:37.34,0:12:38.65,Default,,0,0,0,,Could it be a trap?
Dialogue: 0,0:12:39.07,0:12:45.31,Default,,0,0,0,,No, merely the product of their excessive confidence \Nin our country being unable to crack their cyphers.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:56.84,0:12:59.97,Default,,0,0,0,,We've been given some extremely complicated homework.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:00.43,0:13:04.84,Default,,0,0,0,,You already had your chance to look at the data we have. \NNow ask your questions.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:04.84,0:13:09.53,Default,,0,0,0,,Mr. Yamamoto's escorts may be few, \Nbut there are also Zeros stationed on Bougainville.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:10.16,0:13:12.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Our squadron only has the Lockheed P-38s. {The 1,000-mile flight, with extra fuel allotted for combat, was beyond the range of the F4F Wildcat and F4U Corsair fighters then available to Navy and Marine squadrons based on Guadalcanal. The mission was instead assigned to the 339th Fighter Squadron, 347th Fighter Group, whose P-38G Lightning aircraft, equipped with drop tanks, were the only American fighters in the Pacific with the range to intercept, engage and return. - I think he's worried because it's a heavy fighter, vulnerable if a swarm of a superior number of more agile zeroes engulfs it}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:12.75,0:13:17.38,Default,,0,0,0,,How are we to get close to Yamamoto, \Nwhile staying clear of Bougainville? {nc what he means: いくら山本の一番近くにいてもそれじゃ文猿ビルまでは飛べませんよ}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:17.38,0:13:20.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Answer: certainly, Bougainville has some Zeros stationed on it.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:20.67,0:13:25.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Therefore, you'll attack Mr. Yamamoto \Nbefore he touches down in Bougainville.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:25.44,0:13:29.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Major Mitchell, it's time to explain your plan \Nfor the remaining part. {https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_W._Mitchell_(United_States_Air_Force)}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:29.96,0:13:33.45,Default,,0,0,0,,If we're to tackle this homework, \Nhere's the solution I came up with. {not sure what he means: もしこの宿題が解けたら指揮官は俺がやることになる - If I can solve this homework, I will be the commander.}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:33.93,0:13:36.10,Default,,0,0,0,,So we already have the answer we need to arrive at. {そこで宿題の回答を出してみた}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:36.10,0:13:40.89,Default,,0,0,0,,The target is Bougainville, \Nabout 600 km from our base.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:41.47,0:13:45.09,Default,,0,0,0,,First problem is "how do we fly there \Nwithout the enemy spotting us?"
Dialogue: 0,0:13:45.09,0:13:47.80,Default,,0,0,0,,The answer is, we'll use sea skimming to get there. {, we'll fly an at extremely low altitude}
Dialogue: 0,0:13:47.80,0:13:53.53,Default,,0,0,0,,Should the key objective Yamamoto change the course of his flight, wouldn't we miss him in this vast Pacific Ocean? {/pass by each other }
Dialogue: 0,0:13:53.53,0:13:56.36,Default,,0,0,0,,Exactly. That is the most worrisome point.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:57.33,0:14:00.16,Default,,0,0,0,,The distance from here to Bougainville is 600 km.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:00.16,0:14:04.61,Default,,0,0,0,,But it's only 500 km from Rabaul to Bougainville \Nfor Mr. Yamamoto.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:05.38,0:14:06.37,Default,,0,0,0,,A 100 km difference.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:07.88,0:14:13.37,Default,,0,0,0,,There's only one point in the Southern Pacific \Nwhere these two lines would most likely collide. {it'd make sense if he was talking about time, but no, it's clearly "line"}
Dialogue: 0,0:14:13.92,0:14:16.33,Default,,0,0,0,,So the next problem is how to find that point.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:16.33,0:14:17.87,Default,,0,0,0,,And what's your answer?
Dialogue: 0,0:14:17.87,0:14:19.07,Default,,0,0,0,,The only one possible.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:20.06,0:14:24.38,Default,,0,0,0,,Take off one hour before Mr. Yamamoto \Nand ambush him on the way.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:24.38,0:14:28.26,Default,,0,0,0,,Yamamoto is a punctual man \Nwho always adheres to his promises.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:28.70,0:14:32.76,Default,,0,0,0,,I wonder if he really is a man of his word. \NThe attack on Pearl Harbor was a sucker punch. {/a surprise attack}
Dialogue: 0,0:14:32.76,0:14:36.81,Default,,0,0,0,,No, originally, he planned to launch that attack \Nafter the war had been declared. {いやあれはあくまで戦線布告後に攻撃開始する作戦だった}
Dialogue: 0,0:14:37.36,0:14:42.17,Default,,0,0,0,,But at that same time, the staff at the Japanese embassy in Washington messed up and missed the deadline. {legend: they sent the declaration about an hour before attacking pearl harbor, but the embassy spend 6 hours decyphering it; funnily enough, the american MIS intercepted and decoded it before the embassy itself did, lol}
Dialogue: 0,0:14:42.17,0:14:46.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Yamamoto didn't know that \Nand attacked Pearl Harbor on the scheduled time.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:47.01,0:14:49.30,Default,,0,0,0,,Now, this is the final plan, so take notes. {no clue what he means by "I'll say the final decision now so make note / じゃあ最終決定を言うからメモしてくれ"}
Dialogue: 0,0:14:49.30,0:14:53.01,Default,,0,0,0,,Course 1 - 133 km. {assumed "journey; course; distance; march; flight; drive; leg (of a journey, relay race, etc.)"}
Dialogue: 0,0:14:53.01,0:14:54.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Cardinal direction - 265 degrees.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:54.89,0:14:59.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Speed - 360 km/h. Flight time - 55 minutes. \NSimilarly, in the following...
Dialogue: 0,0:15:00.19,0:15:06.43,Default,,0,0,0,,Course 2. 141 km. Cardinal direction - \N240 degrees. 27 minutes.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:07.20,0:15:13.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Course 3. 200 km. Cardinal direction - \N305 degrees. Fight time 38 minutes.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:14.92,0:15:19.46,Default,,0,0,0,,If things go well, we'll be sure \Nto run into the enemy before 8 a.m. That's all.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:22.99,0:15:26.69,Default,,0,0,0,,They've done their homework remarkably well. \NStill, Commander Layton,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:26.69,0:15:32.99,Default,,0,0,0,,even in World-War I, no enemy Commander-in-Chief had ever been disposed of in this manner.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:32.99,0:15:38.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Mr. President, sir, Yamamoto was the planner \Nbehind the sneak attack on Pearl Harbor.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:38.00,0:15:40.89,Default,,0,0,0,,Don't let it deter you. \NWe're giving him his own medicine. {quits; even; square​}
Dialogue: 0,0:15:41.44,0:15:43.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Please pass down a decision.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:43.45,0:15:45.51,Default,,0,0,0,,He'll fly in just 2 days.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:46.40,0:15:49.93,Default,,0,0,0,,It's regrettable that we have to do away \Nwith a man like Yamamoto.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:35.32,0:16:38.51,Default,,0,0,0,,Admiral, let me board the first plane.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:38.51,0:16:44.10,Default,,0,0,0,,Don't forget that our navy's custom is to have the superior ranks fly the first plane. That would be me today. {no clue what he means: first plane is for the commander to ride - we're in trouble if you forget that, I'm the commander today / 長官一番機には私が乗りましょう 一番機には指揮官が乗るものだということを忘れてもらっちゃ困るな 今日は俺が指揮官だよ }
Dialogue: 0,0:16:44.10,0:16:45.02,Default,,0,0,0,,Okay...
Dialogue: 0,0:17:52.72,0:17:58.72,Default,,0,0,0,,The first plane was carrying Admiral Yamamoto, Navy Surgeon General Takada, and Adjutant Fukuzaki. {https://ja.wikipedia.org/wiki/%E9%AB%98%E7%94%B0%E5%85%AD%E9%83%8E / https://www.tracesofwar.com/persons/84119/Fukusaki-Noburu.htm}
Dialogue: 0,0:17:58.72,0:18:04.69,Default,,0,0,0,,While Chief of Staff Ugaki and Aviation Adviser Muroi \Nwere both on board the second plane. {https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matome_Ugaki#World_War_II / no page for muroi}
Dialogue: 0,0:18:08.69,0:18:13.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Among the Japanese aviators, \Nthis Navy Type 1 attack bomber was known as "Cigar."
Dialogue: 0,0:18:13.49,0:18:17.83,Default,,0,0,0,,While the American pilots \Neither called it "Betty" or "Lighter." {The Allied reporting name was "Betty".[2]\N\NDesigned to a strict specification to succeed the Mitsubishi G3M already in service, the G4M boasted very good performance and excellent range and was considered the best land-based naval bomber at the time.[2] This was achieved by its structural lightness and an almost total lack of protection for the crew, with no armor plating or self-sealing fuel tanks.[3] The G4M was officially adopted on 2 April 1941 but the aforementioned problems would prove to be a severe drawback, often suffering heavy losses; Allied fighter pilots nicknamed the G4M "The Flying Lighter" as it was extremely prone to ignition after a few hits.[2][1][3] It was not until later variants of the G4M2 and G4M3 that self-sealing fuel tanks, armor protection for the crew and better defensive armament was installed.}
Dialogue: 0,0:18:18.28,0:18:22.80,Default,,0,0,0,,It was designed to be extremely lightweight, \Nso as to extend its operational range.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:22.80,0:18:27.42,Default,,0,0,0,,Which in practice produced the serious drawback \Nof it being highly flammable when attacked.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:38.10,0:18:41.47,Default,,0,0,0,,Lost another one. 16 remain.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:41.47,0:18:45.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Well, whatever. The enemy may have his Yamato soul, \Nbut we here also have our Yankee soul.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:45.60,0:18:49.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Speaking of which, it's almost about time \Nfor our appointed meeting with the gentleman Yamamoto.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:56.70,0:18:59.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Admiral, 10 minutes until touchdown.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:59.00,0:19:00.70,Default,,0,0,0,,Okay. Good.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:00.70,0:19:03.20,Default,,0,0,0,,If so, Admiral, we should start getting ready to get off. {/preparing for landing}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:03.20,0:19:04.54,Default,,0,0,0,,Getting ready, right.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:04.54,0:19:08.25,Default,,0,0,0,,When I meet these soldiers would laughing make a good first impression? {lit: when I meet ... for the first time, should I laugh?}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:09.67,0:19:12.31,Default,,0,0,0,,Or perhaps I should bear myself solemnly? {dignity; majesty; solemnity; gravity}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:33.54,0:19:35.99,Default,,0,0,0,,I wonder if we showed up a little too early. {guess}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:46.58,0:19:49.96,Default,,0,0,0,,They're here! \NSince we found them, might as well use radio now. {HA's}
Dialogue: 0,0:19:51.46,0:19:54.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Enemy plane spotted! \NAt 11 o'clock! Altitude 2000.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:54.46,0:19:59.49,Default,,0,0,0,,Thank you! Mitchell speaking. Engage with all aircraft. \NBetty spotted. Lose the drop tanks! {believing HA, can't get half of the words}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:05.48,0:20:06.98,Default,,0,0,0,,Enemy aircraft!
Dialogue: 0,0:20:08.91,0:20:11.98,Default,,0,0,0,,No need to panic. Our base is nearby.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:15.63,0:20:16.50,Default,,0,0,0,,Enemy aircraft!
Dialogue: 0,0:20:16.50,0:20:17.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Shit!
Dialogue: 0,0:20:19.95,0:20:21.56,Default,,0,0,0,,Protect the Admiral!
Dialogue: 0,0:20:33.80,0:20:37.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Which one is carrying Yamamoto? \NWhatever, I can just shoot down both!
Dialogue: 0,0:20:38.80,0:20:40.82,Default,,0,0,0,,Payback for Pearl Harbor! {no clue what's kateki here, was "soul" in HA which is clearly wrong}
Dialogue: 0,0:20:50.49,0:20:51.48,Default,,0,0,0,,Are you okay?
Dialogue: 0,0:20:56.49,0:20:57.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Pull up! {/nose (of plane)}
Dialogue: 0,0:21:28.98,0:21:30.18,Default,,0,0,0,,Hello, Betty. {g}
Dialogue: 0,0:21:37.83,0:21:38.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Get this!
Dialogue: 0,0:21:38.86,0:21:40.36,Default,,0,0,0,,Ah! Admiral!
Dialogue: 0,0:21:40.36,0:21:41.86,Default,,0,0,0,,Admiral!
Dialogue: 0,0:21:54.46,0:21:58.75,Default,,0,0,0,,Admiral, it's our fault! \NPlease try to hang on. {nc what he means by "regrettable; unfortunate; disappointing; vexing"}
Dialogue: 0,0:22:00.31,0:22:01.59,Default,,0,0,0,,Admiral!
Dialogue: 0,0:22:08.89,0:22:10.39,Default,,0,0,0,,Admiral!
Dialogue: 0,0:22:10.39,0:22:12.81,Default,,0,0,0,,The admiral's plane was shot down! It's falling! {no clue whats yushiro, was "Don't lose sight of the Admiral's plane. It was attacked." - clearly wrong}
Dialogue: 0,0:22:41.42,0:22:44.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Mitchell speaking. \NTo all aircraft, both Bettys are downed!
Dialogue: 0,0:22:44.76,0:22:49.45,Default,,0,0,0,,Main objective achieved. \NDisengage and retreat, we're due some medals! {nc whats after kunsho, was "Run away if you want a medal."}
Dialogue: 0,0:22:58.54,0:23:02.00,Default,,0,0,0,,If only... If only I boarded the first plane instead...
Dialogue: 0,0:23:02.79,0:23:06.35,Default,,0,0,0,,When, in an ironic twist of fate,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:06.35,0:23:11.01,Default,,0,0,0,,the man who tried his utmost to avoid a war, had to personally take the reins of the fighting,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:11.51,0:23:15.25,Default,,0,0,0,,he stood his own and fought ferociously.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:16.06,0:23:20.81,Default,,0,0,0,,And he probably knew that his end \Nwould come sooner than later. {lit: before long comes the end of his fate, he knew it}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:21.33,0:23:25.88,Default,,0,0,0,,Yamamoto lsoroku's death \Nwas by no means a thoughtless one.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:25.88,0:23:31.47,Default,,0,0,0,,He believed that by dying \Nhe would pave the way for what is to come next. {not sure what he means: 彼は死ぬことによって後に続くものを信じた - By dying he believed in what would follow.}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:32.10,0:23:40.19,Default,,0,0,0,,This tragic episode served to teach us that the way to win the war is to know your enemy really well. {/one-act play}{really wanted to include https://www.goodreads.com/quotes/17976-if-you-know-the-enemy-and-know-yourself-you-need here but sadly the message is too different}
Dialogue: 0,0:23:40.19,0:23:44.46,Default,,0,0,0,,Even to this day, the first one \Nto acquire the most accurate information
Dialogue: 0,0:23:44.46,0:23:47.80,Default,,0,0,0,,is most likely to pass down a triumphant decision.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:48.42,0:23:57.16,Default,,0,0,0,,The death of one man, Yamamoto Isoroku, would eventually \Nlead to the sun setting upon the whole Japanese Empire.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:58.04,0:24:08.05,Sign,,0,0,0,,{\fade(100,0)}The Pacific War taught us the preciousness of peace.\NBut also instilled numerous lessons on how to live.{太平洋戦争はわれわれに平和の尊さを教えたがまた生きるための教訓を数多くのこしている}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:09.68,0:24:12.50,Default,,0,0,0,,November 1942.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:12.50,0:24:17.60,Default,,0,0,0,,To relieve the 30,000 soldiers, \Nleft behind during the Battle of Guadalcanal,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:18.16,0:24:21.16,Default,,0,0,0,,the Japanese fleet, loaded with supplies and ammunition,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:21.16,0:24:24.56,Default,,0,0,0,,headed for Guadalcanal under the cover of darkness.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:24.56,0:24:29.65,Default,,0,0,0,,The American side nicknamed this relief transport fleet \N"The Tokyo Express."
Dialogue: 0,0:24:29.65,0:24:32.05,Default,,0,0,0,,They started raiding it relentlessly.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:32.05,0:24:38.46,Sign,,0,0,0,,Episode 19 \NBattle of Tassafaronga {ルンガ沖夜戦 - technically "Night Battle off Lunga"}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:32.55,0:24:36.17,Default,,0,0,0,,Witness the next week's decision: \NBattle of Tassafaronga.
Comment: 0,0:24:43.11,0:24:43.15,Default,,0,0,0,,{ch}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:44.04,0:24:48.96,Default,,0,0,50,,If you're a man, let's put your strength to test{男だったら　力を試せ}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:48.96,0:24:52.93,Default,,0,0,50,,If you are a man, keep your hopes sizzling{男だったら　希望(のぞみ)を燃やせ}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:52.93,0:24:57.16,Default,,0,0,50,,If you are a man, don't lose your heart{男だったら　くじけるな}
Dialogue: 0,0:24:57.16,0:25:05.61,Default,,0,0,50,,Because there's just you and me, a man and a man{俺もおまえも　男と男}
Dialogue: 0,0:25:05.61,0:25:14.21,Default,,0,0,50,,With crimson blood flowing in our veins all the same{おなじ真赤な　血が通う}
